And though Homer did not write expressly on this subject, yet he has represented LaerteS, the father of his favourite her0, as a wise prince, retiring from publick business, and devoting his latter years to the tillage of his land. Democritus, Xenophon, Aristotle, Theophrastus, and several other Grecian Philosophers, have treated of Agriculture in prose. Among the Romans, Cato the fa- mous Censor has written a treatise of rural affairs, in which he was imitated by the learned Varro. Cato writes like an ancient country gentleman, of much experience3 he abounds in short pithy sentenceS, intersperses his book with moral precepts, and was esteemed as a sort of rural oracle.
